article.description: Dominique Canty scored a career-high 24 points to lead the Comets to a 73-60 victory over the Fever.
article.headline: Comets win third straight, hand Fever first loss of season
article.linkText: Comets win third straight, hand Fever season's first loss
article.story:
HOUSTON (AP) -- Dominique Canty, playing the best game of her career, led the Houston Comets to their third straight win against an undefeated team.

Canty scored a career-high 24 points and paced the Comets to a 73-60 victory over the Indiana Fever on Wednesday night.

After opening the season with a 79-63 loss to San Antonio, the Comets have reeled off wins against Seattle, Sacramento and the Fever, who were a combined 9-0 before playing Houston.

Tina Thompson and Sheryl Swoopes added 12 points each for the Comets, who improved to 3-1 and share the lead in the Western Conference.

Swoopes, who had five assists, left the game with under a minute remaining with an undisclosed injury. She didn't return and she is questionable for Friday's game against Chicago.

Tamika Whitmore scored a team-high 15 points for the Fever (1-4), who played without leading scorer Tamika Catchings. Catchings missed her first game since 2001 because of an arch sprain in her right foot.

"It was a great game, but we'll have to see how the rest of the season goes," said Canty, who surpassed her previous high of 22 points set in the 2000 season with Detroit. "Right now the team is just working really hard and I think our commitment to defense is getting us to where we are."

The Comets led by as many as 21 points in the second half but had to hold off the Fever, who got within seven points with 69 seconds left.

Canty made two free throws with 1:04 remaining.

"Right now, I am just glad we won," Comets coach Van Chancellor said. "I thought Canty was simply outstanding and that might be the best basketball I have seen her play since her senior season at the University of Alabama.

"I just call her number and let her play her game," Chancellor said.

After a 91-70 home win over the New York Liberty on Tuesday, the Fever made just three of their first 14 shots and trailed 22-8 at the end of the first quarter.

Canty scored 11 points, hitting five of her first six shots, as the Comets took a 38-21 lead into the half.

Whitmore was the only player in the Fever starting lineup to make a shot in the first half.

"We just came out of the gate really slow, but we can't make any excuses for the loss," Whitmore said. "We tried to shut down Sheryl Swoopes and Tina Thompson and make somebody else beat us. Dominique Canty did a very good job of stepping up for her team."

Indiana failed in its chance to establish a franchise record for consecutive wins as the Fever's winning streak was snapped at four games. They also missed an opportunity to post their first three-game winning run on the road.
